    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>The concept you are describing is called \"absolute value\", and Java has a function called <a href=\"http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/lang/Math.html#abs(int)\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Math.abs</a> to do it for you.  Or you could avoid the function call and do it yourself:</p>\n\n<pre><code>number = (number &lt; 0 ? -number : number);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>or </p>\n\n<pre><code>if (number &lt; 0)\n    number = -number;\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 21356,
      "reputation" : 47900,
      "user_id" : 51831,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 56,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e05aeaa4a088ed25b57796b8249c8e12?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "jpalecek",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/51831/jpalecek"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 12,
    "last_activity_date" : 1233264323,
    "creation_date" : 1233264323,
    "answer_id" : 493504,
    "question_id" : 493494,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>Use the <code>abs</code> function:</p>\n\n<pre><code>int sum=0;\nfor(Integer i : container)\n  sum+=Math.abs(i);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
