    "question_id" : 493494,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>You're looking for absolute value, mate. <code>Math.abs(-5)</code> returns 5...</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1662,
      "reputation" : 67983,
      "user_id" : 2238,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 76,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/33f7b52ddceb5ed2ffb12400a4cbceb8?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Henrik Paul",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2238/henrik-paul"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1233264344,
    "creation_date" : 1233264344,
    "answer_id" : 493509,
    "question_id" : 493494,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>You want to wrap each number into <code>Math.abs()</code>. e.g.</p>\n\n<pre><code>System.out.println(Math.abs(-1));\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>prints out \"1\".</p>\n\n<p>If you want to avoid writing the <code>Math.</code>-part, you can include the Math util statically. Just write </p>\n\n<pre><code>import static java.lang.Math.abs;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>along with your imports, and you can refer to the <code>abs()</code>-function just by writing</p>\n\n<pre><code>System.out.println(abs(-1));\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
